# 

The user of this system should configure the system.


The system's configuration model is as follows

```python
class SystemConfiguration(models.Model):
    name = models.CharField(db_index=True, primary_key=True, max_length=20)
    target_average_illumination = models.IntegerField(null=False)
    sunrise = models.TimeField(null=False)
    sunset = models.TimeField(null=False)
    mode = models.IntegerChoices(choices=Modes.choices)

    def __str__(self):
        return f"{self.name}-{self.target_total_illumination}-{self.sun_rise.strftime('%m-%d-%Y %H:%M:%S')}~{self.sun_set.strftime('%m-%d-%Y %H:%M:%S')}-{self.mode}"
```

1. name: The name of this configuration. The system can contain multiple configurations. One configuration has its unique name so that it can be used as an ID
2. target_average_illumination: As the name implies, it is the target average illumination the system will offer to plants from `sun_rise` to `sun_set`
3. sunrise: The sunrise time
4. sunset: The sunset time
5. mode: The mode which the system will run in


There will be only 1 mode that is possible as of now.

# Mode 1
This mode is the default mode of the system. In this mode, the system computes the optimal insolation graph from sunrise to sunset and tries to adjust the system to follow the graph

In order to calculate the insolation value, the system uses the following formula.

1. F0: the strongest insolation of the day
2. theta: represents the anle between the system's zenith and the center of the sun. At sunrise, it is -180 degrees and at sunset, it is 180 degrees


_SOURCE: https://sciencing.com/calculate-solar-insolation-8435082.html_

<img width="675" alt="Screen Shot 2022-10-18 at 2 54 59 PM" src="https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/103418311/196530734-a9e150a2-955c-4995-9a8d-551c17762fb1.png">


In order to calculate the expected illumination for a certain time, it uses `DefaultCalculator`

```python
class DefaultCalculator:
    sunrise_ANGLE = -180
    sunset_ANGLE = 180

    def __init__(
        self,
        target_average_illumination: int,
        sunrise: datetime.time,
        sunset: datetime.time,
        period_in_seconds: int = 1,
    )
```

Here, there is a new variable `period_in_seconds`

This represents the period of each data points. I.E., if the `period_in_seconds` is 60 (1 minutes), then the calculator will calculate the expected illumination from `sunrise` to `sunset` every minnute


For example, say the configured `target_average_illumination` is 1000, the `sunrise` is 8 A.M., the `sunset` is 7 P.M., and the `period_in_seconds` is 3600(1 hour)

Then, the system calculates the cumulative illumination the system should receive throughout the day.

```
From 8 AM to 7 PM, there are 11 data points since the period_in_seconds is one hour
Therefore, the total illumination has to be 1000 * 11
```

The calculate can now calculate the expected `F0` because it is possible to calculate the total illumination from the insolation formula

```
If the sunrise is 8 AM(-180 degree) and the sunset is 7 PM(180 degree), it is possible to calculate the approximate zenith angle of each data points

8 AM: -180
9 AM: -180 + (1/11) * (180 - (-180)
10 AM: -180 + (2/11) * (180 - (-180)
11 AM: -180 + (3/11) * (180 - (-180)
and so on...

Since F = cos(zenith angle) * F0

The total illumination is F0 * (The sum of cos(zenith angle) for each data points)
And the total illumniation has to be 1000 * 11

So, it is possible to calculate the F0
```

Since, we not have the angle of Zenith of one data point as well as the `F0`, it is now possible to calculate the expected illumination(`F`) at at any data point.
